02. Abstract

Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer deaths worldwide. Early detection of small growths called nodules in CT scans can significantly improve survival rates. However, manually reviewing hundreds of scan slices is slow and prone to human error.

This project presents a complete web-based application that uses a 3D deep learning model to automatically detect and locate lung nodules in CT scans. The system processes full 3D scan volumes, identifies suspicious regions, and generates diagnostic reports - acting as an AI assistant for radiologists.

Trained on the LUNA16 benchmark dataset (888 CT scans), our model achieves 94.2% detection rate with only 1.79 false alarms per scan, making it suitable as a clinical screening aid.

08. Preprocessing Strategies

Before feeding scans to the AI model, the raw data needs to be cleaned and prepared.

ðŸ”¢

Intensity Normalization

CT scan values are converted to a 0â€“1 scale. Air and bone are clipped to focus only on lung tissue, making it easier for the model to learn.

âœ‚ï¸

Patch Extraction

Full scans are too large for the model. We cut them into small 3D blocks (32Ã—64Ã—64 pixels) that the model can process one at a time.

ðŸ”„

Data Augmentation

Training patches are randomly flipped, rotated, and have noise added. This helps the model learn to recognize nodules in any orientation.

âš–ï¸

Class Balancing

Since most of the lung is healthy tissue, we extract equal numbers of "nodule" and "non-nodule" patches to prevent the model from being biased.

09. Architecture of the Project

The AI model uses a 3D U-Net design - an encoder-decoder network that learns to highlight nodules in scan volumes.

How the Model Works

â¬‡ï¸ Encoder (Compress)

The scan patch passes through 4 stages that progressively shrink the image while extracting important features like edges and textures.

ðŸ”„ Bottleneck (Core)

The deepest layer captures the most meaningful patterns - understanding the overall structure of lung tissue vs. nodules.

â¬†ï¸ Decoder (Expand)

Expands back to original size while using skip connections to recover fine details, producing a pixel-level nodule map.

Key Design Choices

ðŸ§±

Residual Blocks

Each layer has shortcut connections that help the model train deeper without losing information along the way.

ðŸ”—

Skip Connections

Links between encoder and decoder preserve fine spatial details that would otherwise be lost during compression.

âš¡

Mixed Precision Training

Uses both 16-bit and 32-bit math to train 2Ã— faster while using half the memory - crucial for large 3D data.
